## Why CSS Selectors Are Needed

CSS selectors tell the browser **which HTML elements should be styled**.
Without selectors, CSS wouldn’t know *where* to apply colors, fonts, spacing, or layouts.

In short:
**Selectors = target system for styling**

---

## Element Selector

Targets **all elements of a specific HTML tag**.

**Syntax:**

```css
p {
  color: blue;
}
```

**What it does:**
Styles **every `<p>` element** on the page.

---

## Class Selector

Targets elements with a **specific class attribute**.
Classes can be reused across multiple elements.

**Syntax:**

```css
.highlight {
  background-color: yellow;
}
```

**HTML:**

```html
<p class="highlight">Important text</p>
```

**What it does:**
Styles **any element with `class="highlight"`**.

---

## ID Selector

Targets **one unique element** using its ID.
IDs should be used **only once per page**.

**Syntax:**

```css
#header {
  font-size: 24px;
}
```

**HTML:**

```html
<div id="header">Welcome</div>
```

**What it does:**
Styles the **single element** with `id="header"`.

---

## Group Selectors

Apply the **same styles to multiple selectors** at once.

**Syntax:**

```css
h1, h2, p {
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}
```

**What it does:**
Styles **all `<h1>`, `<h2>`, and `<p>` elements** together.

---

## Descendant Selectors

Targets elements **inside another element**.

**Syntax:**

```css
div p {
  color: green;
}
```

**What it does:**
Styles **only `<p>` elements inside a `<div>`**, not all paragraphs.

---

## Basic Selector Priority (Very High Level)

When multiple styles apply, **CSS follows a priority order**:

1. **ID selectors** (highest priority)
2. **Class selectors**
3. **Element selectors** (lowest priority)

**Example:**

```css
p { color: blue; }
.text { color: green; }
#main { color: red; }
```

➡️ An element with all three will be **red** because IDs win.



